<DOC><DOCNO> AP881121-0010 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-11-21-88 2359EST</FILEID><FIRST>r w PM-Congress-Indictments     11-21 0940</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Congress-Indictments,0961</SECOND><HEAD>17 Congressmen, One Delegate, Indicted In Past Decade While InOffice</HEAD><NOTE>Eds: Also in Tuesday AMs report.</NOTE><HEAD>With PM-Garcia-Wedtech, Bjt</HEAD><BYLINE>By KIM I. MILLS</BYLINE><BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Rep. Robert Garcia, indicted in New York onconspiracy charges in the Wedtech corruption scandal, is the 18thperson in the last decade to be indicted on criminal charges whileserving in Congress.   He is also the second Democratic congressman from New York to beindicted for allegedly using his influence on behalf of the WedtechCorp., a minority-owned New York City machine shop that won no-bidU.S. Army contracts. It has since gone bankrupt.   Mario Biaggi, whose former congressional district in New York'sBronx Borough abuts Garcia's, was convicted Aug. 5 of racketeering,mail fraud and accepting bribes from Wedtech in exchange for hisWashington influence.   Biaggi, 71, resigned his House seat Aug. 6 after serving nearly10 terms. He was sentenced Friday to eight years in prison and a$242,000 fine.   Biaggi also was convicted in November 1987 of accepting anillegal gratuity _ a paid vacation _ for helping an ailing shipyardin New York's Brooklyn Borough. He was sentenced to 2{ years inprison and a $500,000 fine in that case. Biaggi is slated to reportto prison authorities on Jan. 9.   Last month, former two-term Rep. Pat Swindall, R-Ga., wasindicted on perjury charges. Swindall, who narrowly lost his seatNov. 8 as a result of the charges, allegedly lied to a grand juryinvestigating a proposed $850,000 home mortgage loan he discussedwith an Atlanta businessman and an undercover agent posing as afinancier. Swindall allegedly denied being told the source of theloan could be illicit drug money.   Swindall's trial began last month but was postponed after a jurorreceived a mailing from his campaign.   Also last month, Fofo I.F. Sunia, American Samoa's formerdelegate to Congress, was sentenced to five to 15 months in prisonfor participating in a payroll-padding scheme that reportedly earnedhim $39,000. Sunia, a Democrat who had served almost four terms,pleaded guilty to conspiring with his chief aide to defraud thegovernment of $130,920 through false payroll claims.   The 51-year-old Sunia resigned his congressional seat Sept. 6. Asa delegate, he was allowed to vote in legislative committees but noton the House floor.   Other members of Congress indicted since 1978:   _Rep. Harold E. Ford, D-Tenn., charged in April 1987 with bank,mail and tax fraud. No trial date has been set.   _Rep. Bobbi Fiedler, R-Calif., indicted Jan. 23, 1986, along withan aide on charges she tried to buy off an opponent for the GOPSenate nomination in California. The charges subsequently weredismissed by a Superior Court judge in Los Angeles; Fiedler lost theprimary.   _Rep. George Hansen, R-Idaho, indicted in April 1983 andconvicted one year later on charges of violating the 1978 Ethics inGovernment Act by failing to report $333,978 in loans and othertransactions on his financial disclosure forms. Hansen was freed inOctober 1987 after serving nearly one year of a five-to-15-monthsentence.   _Sen. Harrison A. Williams Jr., D-N.J., convicted in May 1981 oncharges stemming from the FBI's Abscam investigation, includingconspiracy, bribery, conflict of interest, receiving an unlawfulgratuity and interstate travel in aid of a racketeering enterprise.   Williams resigned from the Senate in March 1982. He was paroledfrom a halfway house in January 1986 after serving nearly two yearsof a three-year sentence at the federal penitentiary at Allenwood,Pa.   Six House members also were indicted as a result of theundercover Abscam investigation, and all served prison terms. Theywere:   Rep. Raymond Lederer, D-Pa., convicted in January 1981 ofconspiracy, bribery, receiving an unlawful gratuity and interstatetravel to further racketeering; Rep. Michael ``Ozzie'' Myers, D-Pa.,convicted in August 1980 of conspiracy, bribery and interstatetravel; Rep. John Jenrette, D-S.C., convicted in October 1980 ofsharing a $50,000 bribe.   Also, Rep. John Murphy, D-N.Y., convicted in December 1980 ofconspiracy, conflict of interest and receiving an unlawful gratuity;Rep. Frank Thompson, D-N.J., convicted in December 1980 of bribery,conspiracy and aiding and abetting in the acceptance of a criminalgratuity; Rep. Richard Kelly, R-Fla., convicted in January 1981 oftaking a $25,000 bribe from an undercover FBI agent and of takingpart in a $250,000 bribery conspiracy.   _Rep. Claude ``Buddy'' Leach, D-La., was indicted in July 1979 oncharges of buying votes in the 1978 election and violating federalcampaign finance laws. He was acquitted of some vote-buying countsand the others were dropped, and a federal appeals court dismissedthe charges of campaign finance law violations.   _Rep. Joshua Eilberg, D-Pa., indicted in October 1978 on federalcharges of illegally receiving compensation to help a Philadelphiahospital get a $14.5 million federal grant. He pleaded guilty inFebruary 1979 and was sentenced to five years' probation and fined$10,000.   _Rep. Daniel J. Flood, D-Pa., indicted in the fall of 1978 on 13counts of bribery, conspiracy and perjury. His trial on 11 countsended in a mistrial in February 1979, and he resiged from the Housein January 1980, citing health reasons, after the House ethicscommittee accused him of 25 rules violations. In February 1980, hepleaded guilty to conspiracy in a plea-bargaining arrangement andwas given a year's probation.   _Rep. Charles C. Diggs Jr., D-Mich., indicted in March 1978 andconvicted in October 1978 on 29 felony counts of illegally divertinghis congressional employees' salaries to his personal use. Censuredby the House in 1979, Diggs resigned from Congress in 1980 andserved seven months of a three-year prison sentence.</TEXT></DOC>